        "label": "KKPS 22 Apr 26",
        "content": "**Date:** 22 Apr 26\n\nClaude vs ChatGPT – A bull case for DELTA\n\nThere is an emerging narrative shift in the US AI market, driven by changing user preferences and feedback dynamics. This is creating a compelling setup for NVIDIA and its broader supply chain. Recent user discussions across platforms such as Reddit and X suggest that Claude Opus 4.7 may be underwhelming relative to expectations, with perceived performance softness vs. Opus 4.6.\n\nA key point of friction appears to be higher cost per token, which is leading developers to optimize usage by reducing context length and compute per query. This, in turn, translates into fewer reasoning steps and lower sampling depth, effectively capping model quality in real world applications. These are what users believe.\n\nThe implication is important. Opus 4.7 is understood to rely heavily on AWS infrastructure and Google TPU based systems, where cost efficiency constraints are becoming more visible at the application layer.\n\nIn contrast, the upcoming ChatGPT 5.5 launch is expected to run natively on NVIDIA's Blackwell architecture. This creates a clear divergence in both performance scalability and cost efficiency at higher compute loads.\n\nThe setup is asymmetric. If ChatGPT 5.5 receives strong user feedback over the next one to two months, it would support the view that NVIDIA-based systems are the best platform for advanced AI models. This could reinforce a winner-takes-all dynamic for NVIDIA's ecosystem, with Delta Electronics as a beneficiary, and create a clear near-term catalyst."
