        "content": "**Date:** 29 Apr 26\n\nKTB – Positive feedback from meeting with CFO\n\nKTB is navigating a cautious macro environment, citing Middle East tensions as a factor for a low 1.4% economic growth this year.\n\nGovernment loans are the key loan growth engine to manage excess liquidity and ensure good asset quality in 1Q.\n\nThe bank targets to grow retail and SME loans to improve profitability in the remaining quarters.\n\nKTB sees an intensifying competition among banks for high-quality borrowers with low-risk profiles.\n\nAs the Government is considering increase public debt to GDP, the bank expects an uptick in government borrowing in 3Q.\n\nIn term of margin, CFO maintains NIM target at 2.35-2.50%, assuming a 1.0% policy rate in FY26.\n\nKTB redeemed THB18b in AT1 debentures in late 1Q26. Hence, we expected a lower the cost of funds starting in 2Q26, helping to defend margins from a full impact of rate cuts.\n\nCET1 Ratio down 90bps QoQ to 18.5% due to AT1 redemption in 1Q26. It is projected to dip another 20bps in 2Q26 due to dividend payments.\n\nKTB targets to grow fee income by 3–5% YoY, driven by wealth management and capital markets.\n\nThe bank is focusing on customer segmentation on high-net-worth individuals and cooperation with associates —KTAXA (Insurance), KTAM (Asset Management), and KTC (Credit card) to capture a larger share of the customer's wallet.\n\nFor non-interest income, 1Q26 performance was bolstered by dividend income from the Vayupak Fund and mark-to-market gains from THAI investment. More gains are expected within 3Q26 following the end of certain lock-up periods.\n\nOn asset quality, KTB has limited direct exposure to the Middle East related (less than 1% of total loans). However, the bank conservatively set 115bps credit cost (75bps normal + 40bps additional) in 1Q26.\n\nManagement has signaled credit cost to stay at the target of 75-115bps in FY26, with no further increases expected.\n\nWe expect the current NPL coverage ratio of 205% is a good provisioning buffer. Management is comfortable letting this glide down to 170% in the mid-to-long term.\n\nKTB is proactively cleaning its balance sheet and likely to set up JV AMC later this year. The bank will offload some loan segments where internal cash collection is not cost-effective, allowing the JV AMC to handle recoveries.\n\nOn shareholder returns, KTB targets to maintain ROE at 10%+ and maintain dividend payout ratio at high level. Note that its payout ratio was 85%, including 19% special dividend.\n\nJesada\nMaybank\n\n---\n\n27 Feb 26\n\nKTB and BBL remain our top pick among big banks.\n\nOn tactical call, if KTB share price reach THB35 in near term, we recommend switch to BBL and see it is a good laggard play.\n\nBBL market cap is only THB330b vs other big banks that market cap are THB460-500b now.\n\nKTB has set a new benchmark for what big banks should return to shareholders. We see KTB dividend is a good peer pressure on BBL's dividend payment.\n\nNote that we conservatively assume BBL to pay THB9.0 DPS, based on 37% payout ratio, for FY25.\n\nJesada\nMaybank"
