        "content": "**Date:** 2 Mar 26\n\nSAK - Key takeaways from Maybank Consumer Finance Day\n\nSAK targets 8-10% loan growth and plans to open 35 new branches (+3% YoY) in FY26.\n\nThe CEO expects loan yield to drop slightly YoY on a growing land title loan.\n\nCost of funds likely to decline 30bps YoY to 4.20% this year. Overall, SAK expects NIM to increase YoY in FY26.\n\nThe CEO guides for stable credit cost at 1.5-1.6% in FY26.\n\nSAK booked one-off THB26m impairment loss in investment in its subsidiaries in FY25.\n\nExcluding this item, net profit would be THB899m, up 6% YoY.\n\nSAK set up new JV company with NTF (CP THB10.3, Not rated) to procure and distribute agricultural products. SAK will spend THB27.5m to hold 55% stake in JV company.\n\nSAK targets THB15-20m earnings contribution per year from interest income and share of profit from JV company.\n\nOur view\n\nWe see upside on our earnings forecast due to (i) profit sharing from new JV company, (ii) an absence of impairment loss in investment and (iii) a decline in cost of funds from the recent policy rate cut.\n\nNote that 95% of its total funding are floating rate bank loans.\n\nWe are positive on its new JV company as SAK would not only receive a profit sharing but also expand loan portfolio to durian farmers in long term.\n\nLoan growth and earnings are likely to pick up YoY in FY26. Loan portfolio was flat YoY as banks have slowdown to offer credit line in title loans in FY25.\n\nOn dividend policy, SAK plans to gradual increase its payout ratio as its D/E ratio remain low at 1.28x as at end 2025.\n\nSAK announced FY25 dividend of THB0.20/sh, implying 5.1% dividend yield.\n\nWe like SAK for its manageable asset quality and decent dividend yield.\n\nMaintain BUY with TP THB4.60.\n\nJesada\nMaybank"
