        "content": "**Date:** 19 May 26\n\nAdditional color on SAWAD’s mobile phone hire-purchase business: the company has partnered with around 7,000 kiosks as well as ADVICE. The business operates under Sleasing, a subsidiary of SCAP.\n\nAfter 18 months of operations, loan outstanding remains below Bt1bn, with NPL balance at only around Bt3m, equivalent to roughly 100 mobile phones.\n\nSAWAD targets to scale the business 2–3x to Bt2–3bn over the next two to three years. Management highlighted that underwriting standards are stricter than peers, requiring down payments and limiting maximum loan tenor to 18 months. Effective interest rate (EIR) is estimated at around 25%.\n\nAs of 2025, Thailand’s lock-phone lending market had total outstanding loans of around Bt26bn, comprising Bt9.3bn from SG Capital, Bt13bn from Samsung Finance, and Bt5.6bn from Ufund (Com7). This translates into around 2.2m accounts versus annual new mobile phone sales of approximately 17m units. Reported NPL ratios stood at 2.4%, 0.8%, and 1.0%, respectively.\n\nGiven SAWAD’s cautious expansion strategy and disciplined underwriting approach, we view its entry into lock-phone lending positively. The segment should provide incremental revenue contribution alongside continued growth in its core title-loan business. We maintain BUY with a target price of Bt30.\n\n---\n\n# SAWAD Idea"
