        "label": "KKPS 2 Mar 26 ①",
        "content": "**Date:** 2 Mar 26\n\n✈️🟣THAI: Key Takeaways from 4Q25 Analyst Meeting\n\n*Overall tone: slightly positive in the short term, supported by strong cabin factors in March. However, if the Middle East conflict continues, there could be downside risks from higher jet fuel prices.\n\n*Management guided that overall forward bookings for March 2026 improved by 6 ppts YoY, driven mainly by strong demand on European routes. Ticket fares on European routes have increased by around 100%, while fares on other routes are also expected to rise due to higher jet fuel costs.\n\n*For flights to Europe that need to avoid Middle East airspace, the additional fuel cost is only around Bt30,000–40,000 per flight, which is relatively small compared with ticket prices increase.\n\n*In the short term, the impact is limited because jet fuel purchases are typically contracted in advance on a weekly and monthly basis. Therefore, higher fuel costs will likely start to affect results from April onward.\n\nFor hedging, THAI uses a zero-cost collar strategy based on Brent crude prices. As Brent has already exceeded the US$70 ceiling, THAI is currently booking hedging gains. The company has hedged 50% of fuel consumption in 1H26 and 30% in 2H26.\n\nManagement believes this provides a competitive advantage in the region, as only THAI and Singapore Airlines actively hedge fuel costs.\n\n*THAI targets ASK growth of 5–6% in 2026, while passenger yield and cabin factor are expected to remain broadly in line with 2025 levels. Operating profit margin is conservatively expected to decline from 21% to the mid-teens, mainly due to higher aircraft maintenance and employee benefit expenses. THAI plans to maintain employee benefit expenses at around 13% of revenue (vs. 11% in 2025).\n\n*THAI's aircraft fleet is expected to increase from 80 aircraft in 2025 to 102 aircraft in 2026, including 14 wide-body and 14 narrow-body aircraft additions. The airline plans to launch new routes to Amsterdam, Auckland, and China, and increase flight capacity on Paris and Munich routes."
