        "label": "KKPS 2 Mar 26 ②",
        "content": "**Date:** 2 Mar 26\n\n✈️🟣THAI: Benefiting from Middle East Airline Disruptions\n\n*Although airlines are the sector most affected by the Middle East war, we believe THAI could benefit from Middle Eastern airlines suspending operations.\n\n*According to THAI's website, tickets from Thailand to major European cities — including London, Frankfurt, Paris, and Milan — are already sold out until mid of March. When tickets are still available, prices are around Bt70,000–80,000 per trip, compared with the normal price of Bt20,000–25,000.\n\n*We also checked with THAI and found that forward bookings as of 4 March for the three main route groups have improved as follows:\n\n•Europe: 89% in Mar-26 vs 78% in Mar-25\n•Australia: 55% in Mar-26 vs 52% in Mar-25\n•Regional: 66% in Mar-26 vs 61% in Mar-25\n\n*European and Australian routes account for 37% and 10% of revenue, respectively, and their main competitors are Middle Eastern airlines.\n\n*Therefore, we believe THAI could be an interesting option for risk-seeking investors, with several short-term catalysts:\n\n1. 1Q26 results are likely to grow QoQ and could exceed market expectations, supported by strong European routes. In addition, THAI has hedged around 50% of fuel consumption in 1H26, helping limit oil price risk.\n\n2. If the Middle East conflict ends quickly, the stock could rebound in line with the airline sector.\n\n3. THAI's share price has fallen 15% since the war, underperforming Singapore Airlines (-8%) and Cathay Pacific (-10%), both of which are airlines benefiting from reduced operations by Middle Eastern carriers."
