        "content": "**Date:** 22 Apr 26\n\nTTB – An equipped B/S during high uncertainty\n\nFortifying balance sheet\n\nExtra Provisions: While normal credit costs are low (83bps), TTB booked an additional THB1.6b in provisions to buffer against external shocks, specifically the Middle East conflict, rising energy prices, and the slump in low-income housing prices.\n\nRisk Management: The bank is cautious about the low-income mortgage segment (2.5% of the portfolio) due to oversupply and high rejection rates across the industry.\n\nStrategic loan growth\n\nYield Optimization: To combat declining NIM, TTB is shifting toward high-yield lending (e.g., Home Equity, Unsecured Loans) using a risk-based pricing model.\n\nSelective EV Lending: TTB is being highly selective with EV car loans, favoring mid-to-high income customers because the \"Loss Given Default\" (the actual loss if a borrower fails to pay) is significantly higher for EVs than for traditional combustion engine (ICE) cars.\n\nCorporate concerns\n\nThe bank identifies three primary risks for corporate clients:\n\nInability to pass on rising costs to consumers.\n\nExport hurdles due to Middle East instability and high freight costs.\n\nSupply chain disruptions, particularly a lack of feedstock in the energy and petrochem sectors.\n\nSolid non-interest income\n\nSolid Growth: Non-interest income grew 37% YoY, boosted by the \"You Fight, WE Help\" program (FIDF subsidy) and gains+dividend from the Vayupak fund.\n\nCore Strength: Even excluding special items, core fees from mutual funds, bancassurance, and credit cards grew by 10% YoY.\n\nShareholder value creation\n\nBased on our model, total shareholder return is projected at 10% per year (7% dividend yield + 3% share buyback) through 2025–2028.\n\nWe expect share buybacks to resume after the XD date on April 27, 2026.\n\nWe like TTB for its disciplined cost control and defensive quality-first strategy. Maintain a BUY rating with a TP of THB 2.40.\n\nJesada\nMaybank"
